Subject: Re: [T2] 71 to  rebuild  or replace?  dilemma

To parrot John below, even IF you get a motor from a supposedly "reliable" builder, there is no guarantee that it will not fall apart if it was built bad.  My 71 type 1 had a new motor (the only addition was an 1835 upgrade), and it came apart in about 500 miles (5000 would have been a blessing).  SERIOUSLY came apart.  Could never find out why - I do know they had the component lumps (there were very few parts not ruined) spread out on 2 workbenches, trying to figure out the point of collapse...  They made good, but I was without a car for a few days over that.

I would say - one, talk to people who have dealt with the rebuilders you are considering, to find out *their* impressions and comments, and two, talk in DEPTH with the rebuilders themselves.  KNOW they know what they're doing.

Finally on that - CHECK your anciliary un-changed parts CLOSELY before you put it on your new block.  Nothing worse than taking a new motor, slapping on, say, a wornout distributor, and having the wonky timing ruin your investment the hard way!

Also to the cable issues - hard to remember that a lot of the parts we get are sometimes as old as our machines...  not only may they have been faulty, but they've likely been sitting on a shelf, getting dusty and surface-rusty for, maybe, 40+ years.  Even if I get something "NOS" I look it over like a hawk...

Sus

